1. Regular Function (Normal Function)
Definition:
..> A normal function declared using function keyword.
ex: 
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

Key Features :
------------------- >
Feature	Behavior
Has its own this	Yes — this depends on how the function is called
Can be used as constructor	Yes → new User()
Can have arguments object	Yes
Hoisted	Yes (function declarations only)

What is the arguments object ?
The arguments object is a built-in object available inside regular functions.
It contains all the arguments passed to that function — even if you didn’t define parameters.
ex:
function test() {
  console.log(arguments);
}
test(10, 20, 30);
[10, 20, 30]



ex2:
function sum() {
  let total = 0;
  for (let value of arguments) {
    total += value;
  }
  return total;
}

console.log(sum(1, 2, 3, 4)); // 10



2. Arrow Function (=>)
Definition:
..> A modern, short-hand function syntax introduced in ES6.
ex: const add = (a, b) => a + b;


Key Features:
--------------------- >
Feature	Behavior
Has own this?	❌ No — it “inherits” this from surrounding scope (lexical this)
Can be used as constructor?	❌ No
Has arguments object?	❌ No
Hoisted?	❌ No

function Person() {
  this.age = 0;

  setInterval(() => {
    this.age++;   // arrow function inherits 'this' from Person
  }, 1000);
}


❌ Arrow Functions DO NOT HAVE arguments
Arrow functions do not create their own arguments object.


const test = () => {
  console.log(arguments);
};
test(10, 20, 30);  // we gert error ReferenceError: arguments is not defined

ex 2:
How to fix this in an arrow function?
If you want to handle unlimited parameters in arrow functions, you must use rest parameters:
const test = (...args) => {
  console.log(args);
};

test(10, 20, 30);  // [10, 20, 30]



3. Callback Function
Definition:

A function passed as an argument to another function.

✔️ Not a special type of function
❗ It can be a regular function OR an arrow function

4.  Currying Function :- 
    ..> Function currying is a technique in JavaScript where a function with multiple arguments is transformed into a sequence of functions, each taking one argument at a time.
      Instead of calling a function like fn(a, b, c),
      we call it like fn(a)(b)(c).

ex:-
    function add(a) {
      return function (b) {
        return a + b;
      };
    }
    
    add(2)(3); // 5

ex:- 
  const add = a => b => a + b;
  add(2)(3); // 5
